description:
Basil Thai Restaurant isn't authentic Thai per se, as several dishes on the menu adopt hints of influence from other cuisines. This certainly doesn't mean they taste any worse though. In fact, they're pretty damn good.

Personally, my main complaint was that we were not notified of the additional cost for rice ($2.50 per cup, jasmine or brown) upon ordering. We only realized the extra charge once the bill arrived. My friend, however, would argue that an even bigger issue was the lack of ice in our waters. I suppose she does have a point. It's been feeling like the Sahara in San Francisco these days. As the great Ned Stark once said, "Brace yourself. Summer is coming."

// Thai Style Omelette ($6) - 3 stars
None of us was really sure what ingredients went into this omelette, but it had soft inner layers and crispy edges. The spicy sauce added a nice kick.

// Stuffed Eggplant ($14.95) - 5 stars
"Eggplant-Wrapped Chicken" would probably have been a more appropriate name for this dish, considering how much juicy chicken was jam-packed into the eggplant.

// Kiow Wan Pla ($19.95) - 4 stars
Since sea bass is such a delicate fish, I was originally worried that the green curry sauce would be too overpowering. Definitely not the case though!
